  "prompt": "Can someone build a product based on an idea he pitched to his ex company, if the company never cared to productize it?",
  "response": "Yes, in most cases, an individual can legally build a product based on an idea they pitched to their former company, provided that certain conditions are met. Here are the key factors to consider:\n\n### 1. **Ownership of the Idea**\n   - If the idea was developed **entirely on your own time, using your own resources, and without using company resources or confidential information**, you likely retain ownership of the idea.\n   - If the idea was developed as part of your job duties (e.g., during work hours or using company resources), it might be considered the company's intellectual property (IP), depending on your employment agreement or local laws.\n\n### 2. **Employment Agreement**\n   - Review your employment contract or any agreements signed with the former company. Many contracts include clauses about IP ownership, non-compete agreements, or freedom to pursue ideas.\n   - If the contract assigns all IP developed during employment to the company, you may not have the right to use or develop the idea without permission.\n\n### 3. **Company's Lack of Interest**\n   - If the company explicitly decided not to pursue the idea (e.g., rejected it in writing or confirmed disinterest), this can strengthen your case for claiming ownership, but it doesn\u2019t automatically grant you rights if the idea was developed under company conditions.\n\n### 4. **Non-Compete Clauses**\n   - Ensure that pursuing the idea doesn\u2019t violate any non-compete or non-solicitation clauses in your employment agreement. These clauses may restrict you from working on similar products or industries for a certain duration after leaving the company.\n\n### 5. **Consult an Attorney**\n   - To avoid legal risks, consult an intellectual property or employment attorney. They can review your specific situation, contracts, and local laws to determine your rights and any potential liabilities.\n\n### 6. **Document Everything**\n   - Keep records of when and how the idea was developed, any communication with the company about the idea, and their decision not to pursue it. This documentation can help protect you if disputes arise.\n\n### Summary\nIf the idea was developed independently, outside of your job duties, and the company showed no interest in pursuing it, you may be able to legally develop the product. However, if the idea was part of your employment responsibilities or tied to company IP, you could face legal challenges. Always seek legal advice to ensure you\u2019re on solid ground.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
